<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Drafting day. The framework + the exoplanet + the writing converge into a Report.</p>
  <p>You have the framework from Block 7 (5–7 criteria, fully justified). You have your locked exoplanet from Block 6. You have your Earth baseline and your Mars failed-habitable analysis. Today you write the Report. The Kepler-22 b worked example uses six sections: <strong>(1)</strong> Why I picked this planet, <strong>(2)</strong> My framework, <strong>(3)</strong> Earth as baseline, <strong>(4)</strong> Mars as failed-habitable case, <strong>(5)</strong> Chosen exoplanet against the framework, <strong>(6)</strong> Cross-case synthesis + verdict + NASA recommendation. Open the worked example handout on your desk while you write.</p>
  <p>Honesty is the move. The strongest verdict isn't the most enthusiastic one — it's the one that names its uncertainty and tells the NASA committee exactly what data would change its mind. From the worked example on Kepler-22 b: <em>"Honest reading: Kepler-22 b passes my framework on the stellar + orbital criteria but probably fails on composition — and composition is the most foundational requirement."</em> That's a defensible verdict. "Kepler-22 b is Earth's twin" is not.</p>
  <p>AI is a writing partner today, and every conversation gets logged. The Planet Hunter is for criterion-by-criterion exoplanet reasoning. The Source Evaluator is for OPVL on the NASA Exoplanet Archive entries you cite. The Skeptic is for stress-testing your verdict before the panel does. Every substantive conversation goes into the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a> — the missing-template gate caps K/U at 3–4 Developing.</p>
</section>

